1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:03,000
Previously on "desperate housewives"...

2
00:00:04,100 --> 00:00:05,700
one was careless...

3
00:00:05,700 --> 00:00:07,200
you put a woman into a coma.

4
00:00:07,200 --> 00:00:09,500
Surely that arouses some kind of emotion.

5
00:00:09,500 --> 00:00:10,500
Well, it doesn't.

6
00:00:10,500 --> 00:00:11,900
You and I are finished.

7
00:00:11,900 --> 00:00:14,000
One said goodbye...

8
00:00:14,500 --> 00:00:16,100
I'm so tired of feeling like a failure.

9
00:00:16,100 --> 00:00:17,500
One almost lost it...

10
00:00:17,500 --> 00:00:19,900
your wife didn't kill herself because I wrote a note.

11
00:00:19,900 --> 00:00:22,700
She killed herself because of what
she did to that poor baby.

12
00:00:22,700 --> 00:00:25,100
And one got exactly

13
00:00:25,100 --> 00:00:27,400
what she deserved.

14
00:00:32,100 --> 00:00:35,800
Gabrielle was waiting for her next great idea.

15
00:00:35,800 --> 00:00:38,800
Her first great idea came when she was 15,

16
00:00:38,800 --> 00:00:42,800
after her stepfather paid her a late-night visit.

17
00:00:42,800 --> 00:00:46,700
She bought a bus ticket to New York the very next day.

18
00:00:46,900 --> 00:00:53,400
Her next occurred five years later when she decided
to seduce a famous fashion photographer.

19
00:00:53,900 --> 00:00:58,400
One week later, she began her career as a runway model,

20
00:00:58,400 --> 00:01:02,000
which soon led to her next great idea --

21
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:05,600
her decision to marry Carlos Solis.

22
00:01:05,600 --> 00:01:10,400
Before she knew it, she had jumped off
the runway and moved to the suburbs.

23
00:01:11,600 --> 00:01:16,500
Her most recent great idea was born out
of her boredom with her new life.

24
00:01:16,500 --> 00:01:21,300
That's how she came to start an affair
with her teenage gardener,

25
00:01:21,300 --> 00:01:25,200
which was cut short by a tragic accident,

26
00:01:25,200 --> 00:01:30,000
so once again, Gabrielle was in need of a great idea.

27
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:33,200
Mrs. Solis, I know you're worried,
but it's going to take time.

28
00:01:33,200 --> 00:01:34,600
Hmm?

29
00:01:35,100 --> 00:01:36,200
What is?

30
00:01:36,200 --> 00:01:37,800
You look sad.

31
00:01:37,800 --> 00:01:40,000
I assume you're thinking about your mother-in-law.

32
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:41,900
Oh, no.

33
00:01:41,900 --> 00:01:44,600
So, uh, what were you thinking about?

34
00:01:45,100 --> 00:01:47,000
My life.

35
00:01:47,800 --> 00:01:49,900
It hasn't turned out like I thought it would.

36
00:01:49,900 --> 00:01:51,200
Oh, honey.

37
00:01:51,200 --> 00:01:53,800
Oh, no, I-I know I shouldn't complain.

38
00:01:54,200 --> 00:01:58,000
It's just there's something missing,
and I don't know what it is.

39
00:01:58,100 --> 00:01:59,700
Do you ever feel that way?

40
00:01:59,700 --> 00:02:01,000
Mm, no.

41
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:04,000
When I go home at night, I sleep like a baby,

42
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:06,900
'cause I know I did something that
day that helped people.

43
00:02:06,900 --> 00:02:08,600
That must be a nice feeling.

44
00:02:08,600 --> 00:02:10,000
Hmm. It is.

45
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:12,700
Of course, there's times I wish
I didn't have to work so hard.

46
00:02:12,700 --> 00:02:15,700
We've got a real nursing shortage here,
and they keep cutting our budget and --

47
00:02:15,700 --> 00:02:17,800
Attention, all available personnel --

48
00:02:17,800 --> 00:02:20,500
code blue, stat, room 214.

49
00:02:20,500 --> 00:02:21,400
Excuse me.

50
00:02:21,400 --> 00:02:23,400
Attention, all available personnel --

51
00:02:23,400 --> 00:02:26,200
code blue, stat, room 214.

52
00:02:28,400 --> 00:02:30,500
Damn it, get a doctor in here! I don't have an airway.

53
00:02:30,600 --> 00:02:32,300
No time. I have to intubate.

54
00:02:32,700 --> 00:02:35,300
Mr. Getz? Mr. Getz, listen.

55
00:02:35,300 --> 00:02:36,900
You're not dying on me, okay?

56
00:02:36,900 --> 00:02:39,200
This tube is to help you breathe.

57
00:02:39,200 --> 00:02:40,900
I need you to be brave now.

58
00:02:40,900 --> 00:02:45,300
It was then that Gabrielle got her next great idea.

59
00:02:47,400 --> 00:02:54,600
She decided to throw the first annual Sacred Heart charity
fashion show to raise money for more nursing staff.

60
00:02:54,600 --> 00:02:56,500
Gabby, Gabby, I can't do it.

61
00:02:56,500 --> 00:02:58,800
I cannot walk down a runway in one of these dresses.

62
00:02:58,800 --> 00:03:00,500
They all make me look so fat.

63
00:03:00,500 --> 00:03:02,100
Please get someone to take my place. Please.

64
00:03:02,100 --> 00:03:03,100
- Betty, listen to me.
- No, no, please --

65
00:03:03,100 --> 00:03:05,100
listen, Betty, okay?

66
00:03:05,100 --> 00:03:06,900
You're not quitting on me now.

67
00:03:06,900 --> 00:03:08,000
We're going to find you a gown.

68
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:11,000
It's going to be black and slimming,
and you're going to look great.

69
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:13,700
I need you to be brave now.

70
00:03:13,700 --> 00:03:14,400
Okay.

71
00:03:14,400 --> 00:03:20,500
And that night, when she went to bed,
Gabrielle slept like a baby.

72
00:03:58,200 --> 00:04:02,400
Episode 8 : Suspicious Minds

73
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:07,400
News of the fashion show spread quickly on Wisteria Lane.

74
00:04:08,200 --> 00:04:10,200
Though the event was for charity,

75
00:04:10,200 --> 00:04:14,500
Gabrielle soon discovered when it
came to the latest fashions,

76
00:04:14,700 --> 00:04:17,300
women are seldom charitable.

77
00:04:18,400 --> 00:04:22,400
No one knew this better than Edie Britt.

78
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:31,200
She understood that treachery never goes out of style.

79
00:04:31,200 --> 00:04:32,600
& nbsp;

80
00:04:32,600 --> 00:04:33,900
Susan.

81
00:04:33,900 --> 00:04:35,700
Give me the dress.

82
00:04:37,500 --> 00:04:39,100
I gave it a shot.

83
00:04:39,100 --> 00:04:41,000
Hmm.

84
00:04:42,300 --> 00:04:42,900
Hi, Helen.

85
00:04:42,900 --> 00:04:43,500
Hi.

86
00:04:43,500 --> 00:04:44,600
How's the dress fitting?

87
00:04:44,600 --> 00:04:47,600
Great. Maybe it could be taken
out in the shoulder a little.

88
00:04:47,600 --> 00:04:49,500
Sure, no problem.

89
00:04:51,600 --> 00:04:52,800
There you go.

90
00:04:53,400 --> 00:04:56,500
You know, Gabrielle, I-I never thanked you properly.

91
00:04:56,500 --> 00:04:56,900
For what?

92
00:04:56,900 --> 00:04:58,600
For what you did for my son.

93
00:04:58,600 --> 00:05:02,500
It was so nice of you to hire John as your gardener.

94
00:05:02,900 --> 00:05:05,500
Believe me, it's been my pleasure.

95
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:06,800
How's he doing?

96
00:05:06,800 --> 00:05:08,100
Good. Good.

97
00:05:08,100 --> 00:05:11,200
I hear he's dating Danielle Van De Kamp.

98
00:05:11,200 --> 00:05:15,200
Oh, for now. I think it's just a matter of
time before they break up for good.

99
00:05:15,200 --> 00:05:16,400
What's wrong?

100
00:05:16,400 --> 00:05:20,300
Oh, she just seems to want much more of
a relationship than he does.

101
00:05:20,300 --> 00:05:23,700
You remember what it was like dating teenage boys.

102
00:05:23,700 --> 00:05:25,000
V aguely.

103
00:05:25,500 --> 00:05:26,000
Thank you.

104
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:28,500
No, you tell that son of a bitch Tanaka
that if he doesn't call me in an hour,

105
00:05:28,500 --> 00:05:31,800
I'm going to go down to his office,
find him, and kick his ass.

106
00:05:35,400 --> 00:05:37,000
Ladies.

107
00:05:40,500 --> 00:05:41,600
Trouble at work?

108
00:05:41,600 --> 00:05:42,700
I don't know what his problem is.

109
00:05:42,700 --> 00:05:44,700
He's making money left and right.

110
00:05:44,700 --> 00:05:46,500
I just wish he'd relax.

111
00:05:46,600 --> 00:05:50,100
Crap, crap, crap.

112
00:05:50,100 --> 00:05:52,700
I'm telling you, all of the good dresses are taken.

113
00:05:52,700 --> 00:05:54,700
Now what the hell am I supposed to wear?

114
00:05:54,700 --> 00:05:57,100
Well, Mrs. Huber never showed up.

115
00:05:57,100 --> 00:05:58,800
Why don't you wear this one?

116
00:06:01,900 --> 00:06:04,700
This is an old lady dress.

117
00:06:05,200 --> 00:06:06,900
You won't even be able to see my body.

118
00:06:06,900 --> 00:06:09,800
That is so like you, Edie.
You're always thinking of others.

119
00:06:09,800 --> 00:06:11,600
So why isn't Mrs. Huber here?

120
00:06:11,600 --> 00:06:14,200
Last I heard, she went to visit her sister.

121
00:06:14,200 --> 00:06:18,200
I just can't believe that Martha
would agree to wear this.

122
00:06:18,200 --> 00:06:21,700
She always said she'd never
be caught dead in black.

123
00:06:22,800 --> 00:06:25,500
Sadly for Mrs. Huber,

124
00:06:25,500 --> 00:06:28,800
this was no longer the case.

125
00:07:00,300 --> 00:07:01,100
Hey, mom.

126
00:07:01,100 --> 00:07:03,000
Julie, you'll never guess who you got a letter from.

127
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:05,600
Zach. Isn't that weird --him writing you?

128
00:07:05,600 --> 00:07:06,900
Yeah.

129
00:07:06,900 --> 00:07:08,900
Well, open. Open, open, open.

130
00:07:08,900 --> 00:07:10,900
He -- he could have said something about Dana.

131
00:07:10,900 --> 00:07:12,300
I'll read it later.

132
00:07:12,300 --> 00:07:14,400
Later? What's wrong with now?

133
00:07:14,400 --> 00:07:16,900
I've got tons of homework, mom.

134
00:07:17,400 --> 00:07:19,400
Julie, what's going on?

135
00:07:20,200 --> 00:07:23,100
This isn't the first letter I've gotten from Zach.

136
00:07:23,100 --> 00:07:26,300
We've been writing each other
the last couple of weeks.

137
00:07:27,100 --> 00:07:28,100
Are you mad?

138
00:07:28,100 --> 00:07:30,100
No.

139
00:07:30,100 --> 00:07:34,900
Just when I was your age, my pen pal lived on
a farm in Ohio, not in a mental institution.

140
00:07:34,900 --> 00:07:37,500
You know, that letter is one notch above prison mail.

141
00:07:37,500 --> 00:07:39,000
Zach's not crazy.

142
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:42,400
He's just upset over his mom, and his dad
doesn't even seem to care.

143
00:07:43,300 --> 00:07:45,900
He just needs a friend.

144
00:07:49,800 --> 00:07:51,100
I packed the diapers,

145
00:07:51,100 --> 00:07:54,800
I'm getting the juice boxes and the carrot sticks --

146
00:07:54,800 --> 00:07:55,400
sunscreen?

147
00:07:55,400 --> 00:07:57,000
Got it.

148
00:07:57,000 --> 00:07:59,400
I go pick up the boys, we hit the park,

149
00:07:59,400 --> 00:08:03,900
and that should give you a good couple of hours.

150
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:08,500
Enjoy the vacation.

151
00:08:10,500 --> 00:08:11,900
What?

152
00:08:12,300 --> 00:08:17,200
While you're gone, I'll be here paying bills
and sorting laundry and cooking dinner,

153
00:08:17,200 --> 00:08:20,700
so what part of that sounds like a vacation?

154
00:08:20,800 --> 00:08:23,500
Okay, right, you know what?
We'll pick up dinner.

155
00:08:23,500 --> 00:08:28,600
and you just take a hot bath, relax, recharge.

156
00:08:28,600 --> 00:08:31,000
& nbsp;

157
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:32,100
Okay, I get it.

158
00:08:32,100 --> 00:08:35,200
It's going to take more than a hot bath to recharge,

159
00:08:35,200 --> 00:08:38,200
but, uh, don't forget, I'm here all week.

160
00:08:38,200 --> 00:08:39,500
Then what?

161
00:08:42,500 --> 00:08:44,200
And then we go back to normal?

162
00:08:44,200 --> 00:08:47,100
Tom, our last version of normal had me popping pills.

163
00:08:47,100 --> 00:08:50,800
Normal is a bad, bad plan.

164
00:08:50,800 --> 00:08:54,700
Okay, so we'll put our heads together,
and we'll come up with a solution.

165
00:08:54,700 --> 00:08:58,000
I think we need to hire a nanny full-time.

166
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:00,300
That's just such a big, big commitment.

167
00:09:00,300 --> 00:09:03,200
I know, and I know we can't afford it,

168
00:09:03,200 --> 00:09:07,200
and I know everything that's happened is my fault,

169
00:09:07,200 --> 00:09:09,500
but if I don't get some help,

170
00:09:09,500 --> 00:09:13,300
there's an excellent chance I will lose my mind.

171
00:09:15,600 --> 00:09:18,000
Okay, well, then, we have to make it work.

172
00:09:22,300 --> 00:09:25,500
Next up, the 200-meter freestyle.

173
00:09:28,200 --> 00:09:29,600
It's just not right.

174
00:09:29,600 --> 00:09:30,200
What?

175
00:09:30,200 --> 00:09:35,000
A woman is in a coma because of Andrew,
and there he is, happy as a clam.

176
00:09:35,100 --> 00:09:38,200
Well, we grounded him, we took
away the tv in his room.

177
00:09:38,200 --> 00:09:39,900
How many more ways you want to punish him?

178
00:09:39,900 --> 00:09:42,300
Swimmers, take your marks.

179
00:09:48,700 --> 00:09:51,000
I think we should make him quit the swim team.

180
00:09:52,200 --> 00:09:55,800
Bree, this is the one thing in his
life that he's passionate about.

181
00:09:55,800 --> 00:09:59,600
Well, maybe if we take it away from him,
then he'll start to understand what he did.

182
00:09:59,600 --> 00:10:02,400
He has not shown an ounce of
remorse since the accident.

183
00:10:02,400 --> 00:10:03,800
Of course he feels bad.

184
00:10:03,800 --> 00:10:05,900
He's just, you know, keeping up a facade.

185
00:10:05,900 --> 00:10:07,500
Well, he's doing a fabulous job.

186
00:10:07,500 --> 00:10:10,000
Look, if we take him off the swim team,

187
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:12,100
he'll lose his shot at an athletic scholarship,

188
00:10:12,100 --> 00:10:13,900
and then he's never going to forgive us.

189
00:10:13,900 --> 00:10:18,900
Well, if it ensures he grows up with some trace of
humanity, then that's a risk I am willing to take.

190
00:10:18,900 --> 00:10:19,800
Well, I'm not.

191
00:10:19,800 --> 00:10:22,500
That's because you just don't
love him as much as I do.

192
00:10:22,500 --> 00:10:23,600
Well, isn't that nice?

193
00:10:23,600 --> 00:10:25,600
It's just a fact. I'm his mother.

194
00:10:25,600 --> 00:10:27,000
He lived inside of me.

195
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:29,900
He hung out in your womb for a few
months back in the '80s.

196
00:10:29,900 --> 00:10:33,200
Since then, I have grown to love
him just as much as you.

197
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:38,100
What just happened?

198
00:10:38,100 --> 00:10:41,500
That kid you both love so much just won the race.

199
00:11:04,100 --> 00:11:05,500
John.

200
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:09,800
My mom said you needed volunteers, so I volunteered.

201
00:11:10,600 --> 00:11:11,800
Oh.

202
00:11:12,300 --> 00:11:14,300
Finally got the charity bug?

203
00:11:14,400 --> 00:11:16,100
You sound surprised.

204
00:11:16,100 --> 00:11:18,200
No, not really.

205
00:11:18,400 --> 00:11:20,100
You were always a giver.

206
00:11:20,100 --> 00:11:20,900
Would you knock it off?

207
00:11:20,900 --> 00:11:23,000
My mom's right over there.

208
00:11:25,900 --> 00:11:27,200
Have a seat.

209
00:11:28,300 --> 00:11:31,800
You can start by helping us alphabetize
the donation cards.

210
00:11:38,900 --> 00:11:41,300
So word on the street is you and
Danielle might break up.

211
00:11:41,300 --> 00:11:43,400
Maybe. I don't know.

212
00:11:43,400 --> 00:11:45,400
Is that because of me?

213
00:11:46,200 --> 00:11:48,500
Not everything is about you.

214
00:12:01,500 --> 00:12:03,000
Would you stop that?

215
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:05,200
Have you been thinking about me?

216
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:07,300
No.

217
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:09,100
Really?

218
00:12:09,700 --> 00:12:11,500
Could have fooled me.

219
00:12:15,800 --> 00:12:17,400
Hey, do you need any help?

220
00:12:17,400 --> 00:12:19,300
Please. Just pull up a chair.

221
00:12:19,300 --> 00:12:20,300
Oh, gosh.

222
00:12:20,300 --> 00:12:22,600
That's okay. I got it.

223
00:12:31,400 --> 00:12:33,300
Ow! Oh!

224
00:12:43,600 --> 00:12:45,000
Susan, hi.

225
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:46,700
Do you want to help with the seating cards?

226
00:12:46,700 --> 00:12:51,300
Sure. Do you want to tell me why you had your
foot in John Rowland's crotch yesterday?

227
00:12:52,100 --> 00:12:53,200
Oh, that.

228
00:12:53,200 --> 00:12:56,500
Uh, he was helping me adjust the seam in my stocking,

229
00:12:56,500 --> 00:13:00,400
and from your angle, it must have looked a little weird.

230
00:13:00,800 --> 00:13:02,900
You're sleeping with him, aren't you?

231
00:13:03,900 --> 00:13:05,500
Okay.

232
00:13:05,500 --> 00:13:07,600
Yes, but you have to promise not to tell anybody.

233
00:13:07,600 --> 00:13:12,600
Gabrielle, he's in high school, and
it's illegal, and you're married.

234
00:13:12,600 --> 00:13:14,500
If Carlos found out, this would kill him.

235
00:13:14,500 --> 00:13:16,900
It's just sex. It's totally harmless.

236
00:13:16,900 --> 00:13:20,000
How can you call something like this harmless?

237
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:23,600
After everything you know about
what I went through with Karl?

238
00:13:23,600 --> 00:13:25,300
This isn't about you.

239
00:13:25,300 --> 00:13:26,200
Yes, it is.

240
00:13:26,200 --> 00:13:30,700
It's about me and about every other person who
was screwed over by somebody they loved.

241
00:13:30,700 --> 00:13:33,500
When Karl ran off with Brandi, you saw
what a basket case I was.

242
00:13:33,500 --> 00:13:37,300
I was crying, I-I was tearing up his clothes.
I couldn't get out of bed all day.

243
00:13:37,300 --> 00:13:39,900
You were right there. How could you do the same thing?

244
00:13:39,900 --> 00:13:42,500
Okay, how can you compare me to Karl? That's not fair.

245
00:13:42,500 --> 00:13:44,400
You have no idea what my life is like.

246
00:13:44,400 --> 00:13:45,600
Well, why don't you enlighten me?

247
00:13:45,600 --> 00:13:48,100
You're beautiful, you have more
money than you can spend,

248
00:13:48,100 --> 00:13:49,700
and you have a husband who adores you.

249
00:13:49,700 --> 00:13:51,100
No, he doesn't adore me.

250
00:13:51,100 --> 00:13:52,800
He adores having me.

251
00:13:52,800 --> 00:13:55,300
That's a rationalization, and you know it.

252
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:00,000
See you at the show.

253
00:14:03,100 --> 00:14:05,200
Okay, honey. There you go.

254
00:14:05,200 --> 00:14:07,000
How many nannies did you interview?

255
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:10,700
10. 10, each one more incompetent than the last.

256
00:14:10,700 --> 00:14:12,800
One actually asked me --

